> In the modern world of business, it is useless to be a creative, original thinker unless you can also sell what you create.
> <cite>David "The Father of Advertizing" Ogilvy, 19xx</cite>

I love the idea of free - [as in freedom, not as in beer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gratis_versus_libre) - and open source software. The democratization of software brings so much good to the world that it's almost hard to quantify. It enables individual developers to peer into large applications and learn how they function. It enables large corporations to throw their weight onto other projects. It enables the average end user to utilize software that follows open, common standards.

As a direct consequence, I love Linux. Linux's impact on the world of technology is vast, in due part because anyone can modify it. It's been made to run on [phones](https://www.android.com/), [mainframes](https://www.ibm.com/it-infrastructure/z/os/linux) and [refrigerators](https://www.samsung.com/us/explore/family-hub-refrigerator/overview/). You can even force it, albeit kicking and screaming, to run on [an 8-bit microcontroller](https://hackaday.com/2012/03/28/building-the-worst-linux-pc-ever/).

So it might surprise you to learn that I use Windows.

